The <a href="/site/apidocs/org/apache/juneau/marshall/stream/TokenReader.html" target="_blank">TokenReader</a> /
<a href="/site/apidocs/org/apache/juneau/marshall/stream/TokenWriter.html" target="_blank">TokenWriter</a>
surface exposes structural events one at a time — `START_OBJECT`, `FIELD_NAME`, `VALUE_STRING`,
`END_OBJECT`, etc. — for formats whose wire encoding is already token-shaped.

Available on formats that implement the <a href="/site/apidocs/org/apache/juneau/marshall/stream/TokenReadable.html" target="_blank">TokenReadable</a> /
<a href="/site/apidocs/org/apache/juneau/marshall/stream/TokenWritable.html" target="_blank">TokenWritable</a> role: json, json5, jsonl, cbor, msgpack (read + write), plus jsonschema and jcs (writer-only).

> See the <a href="/site/topics/TokenStreamingBasics#per-format-capability-matrix">per-format capability matrix</a>
> for the full breakdown of which formats expose the token cursor for reading vs writing.

##### Pull side: TokenReader

```java
try (TokenReader r = JsonParser.DEFAULT.parseTokens("{\"a\":1,\"b\":[true,null]}")) {
    while (r.next() != TokenType.END_OF_STREAM) {
        switch (r.getCurrentToken()) {
            case FIELD_NAME   -> handleKey(r.getFieldName());
            case VALUE_STRING -> handleString(r.getString());
            case VALUE_NUMBER -> handleNumber(r.getNumber());
            case VALUE_BOOLEAN -> handleBool(r.getBool());
            case VALUE_NULL   -> handleNull();
            default -> { /* structural */ }
        }
    }
}
```

Key methods:

- `next()` — advances and returns the new current token type.
- `getCurrentToken()` — current token without advancing.
- `getDepth()` — nesting depth (0 at root).
- `getString()` / `getNumber()` / `getNumberLexeme()` / `getBool()` / `getBinary()` — accessors for the current scalar.
- `getFieldName()` — when current token is `FIELD_NAME`.
- `skipChildren()` — fast-forward past the current container's body to its matching end.
- `read(Class)` — br...

The `parseArrayRecords(...)` / `serializeArrayRecords(...)` factories — declared by the
<a href="/site/apidocs/org/apache/juneau/marshall/stream/ArrayRecordReadable.html" target="_blank">ArrayRecordReadable</a> /
<a href="/site/apidocs/org/apache/juneau/marshall/stream/ArrayRecordWritable.html" target="_blank">ArrayRecordWritable</a>
roles — yield a multi-record cursor over the **elements of a top-level wire array**, without
materializing the whole list. This applies to single-rooted formats whose root value happens to be
a list — JSON's `[...]`, CBOR's array major-type, etc.

For naturally-multi-record formats (csv, sse), use `parseRecords` / `serializeRecords`
directly — the wire format IS already a sequence of records. JSONL is also natively
line-delimited; its `parseArrayRecords` / `serializeArrayRecords` simply alias that line
record stream (rather than wrapping the elements in a bracketed `[...]` array).

> See the <a href="/site/topics/TokenStreamingBasics#per-format-capability-matrix">per-format capability matrix</a>
> for which formats support array-record reading/writing and whether each streams O(1) or buffers.

##### Reading large arrays element-by-element

```java
// Wire payload is one big JSON array; we want O(1) memory per element.
try (RecordReader r = JsonParser.DEFAULT.parseArrayRecords(input)) {
    while (r.canRead()) {
        Bean b = r.read(Bean.class);
        process(b);
    }
}
```

##### Writing large arrays element-by-element

```java
try (RecordWriter w = JsonSerializer.DEFAULT.serializeArrayRecords(output)) {
    for (Bean b : sourceOfBeans()) {
        w.write(b);
    }
}
// output is now: [{...},{...},{...}]
```

##### Format applicability

| Format | Reader | Writer | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| JSON / JSON5 | streaming | streaming | O(1) memory per element. |
| CBOR | streaming | streaming | Reader uses indefinite-length array peek (BREAK). Writer always emits indefinite-length so no element count needed. |
| MsgPack | streaming...

`TokenReader`, `TokenWriter`, `RecordReader`, and `RecordWriter` are first-class
`@RestOp`-method parameter types. Declare one in your method signature and the framework picks
the matching parser/serializer based on the request `Content-Type` / response `Accept` and
hands you the cursor.

> See the <a href="/site/topics/TokenStreamingBasics#per-format-capability-matrix">per-format capability matrix</a>
> for which formats can satisfy a `RecordReader` / `TokenReader` / `RecordWriter` / `TokenWriter` parameter.

##### Server-side reader parameter

```java
@Rest(parsers = JsonParser.class)
public class MyResource {

    @RestPost
    public String process(RecordReader r) throws Exception {
        Bean b = r.read(Bean.class);
        return b.name;
    }
}
```

Concrete cursor types work too — declaring `JsonlTokenReader` means only `JsonlParser` is
eligible:

```java
@Rest(parsers = JsonlParser.class, defaultAccept = "application/jsonl")
public class JsonlIngest {

    @RestPost
    public int countRecords(JsonlTokenReader r) throws Exception {
        int n = 0;
        while (r.canRead()) {
            r.read(Bean.class);
            n++;
        }
        return n;
    }
}
```

##### Server-side writer parameter

Declaring a writer parameter flips the response into "user owns the body" mode — the framework
will not later serialize a return value over the same stream:

```java
@RestGet
public void exportLargeArray(RecordWriter w) throws IOException {
    for (Bean b : sourceOfBeans()) {
        w.write(b);
    }
    // close() is the framework's responsibility on return.
}
```

##### Two-layer resolution

Cursor parameter resolution uses two layers:

1. **Declared type filters eligible parsers/serializers.** A `RecordReader` parameter accepts
   any parser that is a `RecordReadable`; a `TokenReader` parameter accepts only parsers that are
   a `TokenReadable`; a concrete `JsonlTokenReader` parameter accepts only parsers whose
   `parseTokens(...)` returns a `Json...

