As of 10.0, `JettyMicroservice` was reshaped — the legacy *subclass* form was retired, and a thin static-call facade
was introduced to collapse the standard `Microservice` + `JettyConfiguration` bootstrap. See
[JuneauMicroserviceJettyBasics](/docs/topics/JuneauMicroserviceJettyBasics) for the new entry point.

`juneau-microservice-jetty` contributes a single [JettyConfiguration](MicroserviceJettyOverview) class that wires Jetty
into the standard [Microservice](JuneauMicroserviceBasics).  Customization is therefore done by **contributing your own
`@Bean` definitions** rather than subclassing.

#### Hooking into the lifecycle

Implement [`MicroserviceListener`](MicroserviceCoreListeners) and expose it as a `@Bean` — every
`MicroserviceListener` bean in the store is invoked on `start()` / `stop()` / config-change events
(start in registration order, stop in reverse order).

```java
@Configuration
public class MyApp {

    @Bean
    Servlet rootResources() { return new RootResources(); }

    @Bean(name = "lifecycle")
    MicroserviceListener lifecycle() {
        return new BasicMicroserviceListener() {
            @Override
            public void onStart(Microservice ms) {
                // custom start-up logic, e.g. warming caches, registering JMX beans, etc.
            }
            @Override
            public void onStop(Microservice ms) {
                // custom shutdown logic
            }
        };
    }
}

public class App {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        Microservice
            .create()
            .args(args)
            .configurations(JettyConfiguration.class, MyApp.class)
            .build()
            .start()
            .startConsole()
            .join();
    }
}
```

